Comment only, out of scope for this PR:

If the goal is to reduce peak memory use, it seems that there's still some waste here as we construct a huge intermediate `centered` value of shape `(n_samples_in_this_sequence, n_components, n_mix, n_features` and then do a single pass over it, immediately reducing away the `n_samples_in_this_sequence` dimensions in the `einsum`.

I reckon the calculation here is is equivalent to this naive bunch of C for loops, that doesn't need to allocate any memory for a huge `centered` array at all:

```
int i, j, k, l;
double acc, centered;

for (j = 0; j < n_components; ++j) {
    for (k = 0; k < n_mix; ++k) {
        for (l = 0; l < n_features; ++l) {
            acc = 0.0;
            for (i = 0; i < n_samples_in_this_sequence; ++i) {
                centered = samples[i, l] - means_before_update[j, k, l];
                acc += post_comp_mix[i, j, k] *  centered * centered;
            }
            c_n[j, k, l] += acc;
        }
    }
}
```

We could implement the logic by writing it in Cython, at some cost to maintainability.  I am not sure there is a clean way to express it in fast pure numpy code, as `einsum` doesn't let us use subtraction in a big tensor expression.

I'm not sure if similar idea could be used to rewrite the other cases of covariance_type.

